article.headline: Broback nets 26 as Golden Gophers hold off Hoosiers
article.linkText: Broback nets 26 as Golden Gophers hold off Hoosiers
article.story:
BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- Jamie Broback needed this kind of 
performance.

Coming off a three-game slump in which she scored a total of 17
points, the Minnesota junior had a season-high 26 points and hit a
clinching 3-pointer with under 2 minutes to go, leading the Gophers (No. 15 ESPN/USA Today, No. 17 AP) over Indiana 69-64 on Monday night.

"This is a game I needed to step up. My main thing was just
bringing confidence and playing hard," Broback said. "Obviously,
with two big home games coming up, that was the biggest thing for
me."

Broback had just seven points in a 21-point loss at LSU on
Saturday, following a season-low two points in a win over Wisconsin
two nights earlier. Minnesota plays No. 12 Purdue and No. 9
Michigan State later this week.

"It was a solid team effort," Minnesota coach Pam Borton said.
"Jamie stepped up and made the big plays. ... When she plays hard
and aggressive, good things happen with her game."

Broback also had nine rebounds and a season-high three
3-pointers, the last after Indiana pulled within 61-57 with just
over two minutes remaining.

"It wasn't pretty, but it went in," she said.

Kelly Roysland tied her career high with 19 points off the bench
as Minnesota's reserves outscored Indiana's 30-7.

"They outplayed us in the first half and we couldn't get the
job done," Indiana coach Sharon Versyp said.

"Jamie is just a tough, tough kid. She loves to get the ball in
her hands," Versyp said. "She's very smart and knows when the
double-teams are coming."

Indiana (8-7, 2-2 Big Ten) overcame a 12-point deficit in the
first half and took its last lead at 41-39 on a fast-break basket
by Jenny DeMuth 7 minutes into the second half. Two baskets by
Broback then started a 13-3 run as the Gophers (10-3, 3-0) took the
lead for good.

A 3-pointer by DeMuth, who led Indiana with 18 points, pulled
the Hoosiers within 54-49. Indiana's next 10 points came on free
throws and the Gophers stayed comfortably in front the rest of the
way.

Cyndi Valentin added 13 points for the Hoosiers and extended her
season free throw streak to 60 in a row, tying an NCAA Division I
record.

Consecutive 3-pointers by Valentin and Nikki Smith to start the
game gave Indiana the early lead. Valentin had seven of the
Hoosiers' first 12 points, but she did not score the rest of the
half, and a flurry of 3-pointers helped Minnesota take control.

Roysland had two 3s during a 14-4 run that put the Gophers up
24-18 with under six minutes to go in the opening period. Then, after
two free throws by DeMuth, Roysland got her third 3, and the
Gophers widened the lead to 33-21 on a basket and free throw by
Broback with 1:28 to go.

Another 3-pointer by Smith and two more free throws by DeMuth
cut it to 33-26 at halftime, then the Hoosiers scored the first
seven of the second half to tie the game at 33. There were three
more ties before the decisive Minnesota run.
